node.text:
A lot of time this year has been gone by staying at home. 

The number of #photoshoots I have done this year has been restricted either due to the #lockdown or due to the #travel bans. All because of this #pandemic.

And even in the photography #assignments that I do, there is an element of anxiety hoping that all goes well and that all the people involved are safe. So far, so good.

It has been a difficult time for a lot of us. Not just for #photographers, but for all freelance creatives, independent professionals, and everyone who is part of a gig economy. I hear you!

The odds are more in favour towards uncertainty than in favour of a clear vision. But, then hoping we all find the collective strength and perseverance to see this phase through.

To life, cheers!

Found this ray of light from a setting sun to light up this self portrait. It conveys my mood these days.

Bengaluru. July 2020.

node.text:
// WHICH CAME FIRST? //?
?
SWIPE ???
?
Certainly the egg for me!?
?
On today's edition of Sunday's Andes, feast your eyes on an Egg Masala my mom conjured up back in May!?
?
Around then, I remember getting very egg-cited about food photography. I began following @abhishekhanna and seeing his stellar work, and I thought to myself - maybe I can give this a try! ?
?
And fortuitously enough - my mom made this sumptuous curry for the day. I shellebrated, because I knew then and there that this would be an Ande Funday. (I'll stop with the bad yolks now, hope they made you crack up xD) My mom had sourced the ripest, reddest tomatoes and I was dying to use them in a shoot. So I grabbed a few from the kitchen, along with some other accoutrements - lemons, garlic, coriander, and some chillies! We also had two chopping boards neatly stacked in the bottom shelf, which I planned to use as the base.?
?
I then proceeded to MasterChef the hell out of that curry - sprinkling the leaves, arranging the accompaniments around the centerpiece in the most decorative manner possible. And finally, I turned on my camera! These are some of my favorite shots from the day :))?
?
I've never really spent much time in the kitchen, besides helping myself to an extra serving of that delish payasam. I spend more time at the dinner table, refining my Michelin Man look. As the popular old saying goes - The best way to a man's heart is through his stomach!?
?
I've been super lazy, forgive me. But I promise I'll get back on track and give you a glimpse into my lockdown journey over the course of the next few weeks!?
?
P.S.: One last thing - Hope this photo was worth the white :P?
?
Shot on Fujifilm XA-5 with 15-45 mm ?
?

Our Sunday motivation is a peek into artist-curator @amipatelart ‘s studio and art style. 
As Ami puts it:

These days a few questions have been playing heavily on my mind to which I have no clear answers... What is life? Can we plan life? Do we control life or does life controls us?
As an artist, I have always worked on this aspect of life and expressed my emotions through woods, metals and colours. For me nature has been always a greatest teacher. In today's context, my belief system seems so relevant. None of us in our dream had imagined that just like that the whole world will come to a halt. Have we abused the Nature too much?
Certainly, it is time to go back to roots... #lockdowndiaries #artinthetimesofcorona #artiststudio #lockdownthoughts #weareinthistogether #artheals

node.text: This is sweet of you, Mandy. Hope the black dog keeps far away! Hugs. ?

The Lockdown Diaries

This week I was reminded of how special the people are in my life. I was going through a bit of a rough patch thanks to an extended visit from my Black Dog. And I know we're all suffering and struggling. Life is hard. 

So on Friday a beautiful box of cakes arrived from a local bakery, Cakes & Desserts. Collette's main clients over the years have been the airline industry, markets and restaurants. Of course, lockdown happened and it meant her business came to a complete standstill. But she reinvented her business with a new product, which she calls the "Little Cake Box". Every week the box changes but always has slices of freshly baked cakes, tarts, pastries and smaller baked items, as well as a special treat, such as chocolate or granola.

You can find her website here: https://www.cakesanddesserts.co.za/

And to Regine Lord, thank you for brightening up my day – and widening my waist-line!

Kolhapur and Satara were the two strongholds of the Marathas. Madhavrao Peshwa built this fort on the borders of the empire and handed over the control of the fort to Patwardhan family of Sangli who later transferred it to Mudholkar Ghorpade. A trench has been built surrounding the fort and is now covered with vegetation. A part of the trench opposite the entrance has been filled to make a road in-way. The two bastions alongside the entrance have been refurbished.The fort has two fortification walls. The outer wall has 18 bastions while the inner one has 8 bastions. The 12 ft base of fortified walls and bastions are built of black rock and the upper remaining part is made of bricks. As we enter the citadel from the inner fortified wall there is a dense vegetation cover and many structural remains have been hidden in here. There is step well. Further to the well in the outer fortified wall there is a secret doorway.

I am usually an open air person. So, while travelling in this costume from Bangalore to Kolkata in the mid of Corona, I was having some  funny thoughts that I'm going to share today:

- I remembered my college days when I once tracked the evidence of the thief who stole my mobile & how finally i got hold of her. And today, looking at me, I feel I am dressed like a burglur with full protection wearing mask, face shield, gloves so that not a trace of fingerprint is visible on any object I steal & nobody should recognize me.

- Secondly, I was thinking that in this generation, almost all science grads aspire to become software engineers. Now, keeping this attire in mind, I guess our next generation would like to be an astronaut from a very tender age itself & will dream of Moon mission soon. Needless to say, for me Bangalore to Kolkata itself was Mars mission!

- Thirdly, new norms of social interaction can come in place. For example; Now-a- days, airhostesses can't smile & greet, so they can blink & greet and that's how Corona will have a great impact on the way we interact socially.

node.text:
Shilpa Anjo @shilpa.anjo,  a Pharma researcher is currently on a career break. Here's her 'lockdown' story:

My baby and I sitting in the balcony watching the sunset along the horizons of the Periyar river where boats paddle across its streams, is our usual evening. In the initial days of the lockdown, I was hopeful that everything will soon get back to normal. But my hopes were crushed by mid-April when Covid cases in India started spiking. 
My husband - a navigational officer, left to sail months ago knowing that he would miss our baby’s little milestones, with hopes of reuniting with us by mid-July. I was eagerly waiting for him to return at least by the time she starts walking. But it sure looks like he is going to miss that too as the sailors could only reach back home when the international flight operations resume. As the wait for this global stand-still to end continues - I miss him. It pains me to see our baby play every day without even realizing she has a father who on the other side is sailing the oceans, eagerly waiting to come home to her. I constantly realized how important it is to not take what you have for granted as for us, spending time together as a family seemed a luxury. It has been almost three months since we went out or had any visitors. Friends and family stayed away in concern of the baby. But now I am perturbed as she is starting to show stranger-anxiety at the mere sight of people passing by. 
This lockdown helped me immensely in changing the way I perceived the world. I learnt it takes just a microbe to bring us humans to our knees and discovered the power of nature to restore itself. People who never once slowed down in their lives are taking a break. These days my husband and I, though shores apart, are co-writing an autobiographical fiction and we are looking forward to get it published by the end of this year. My baby and I still wait here looking forward to little things like these which means the world to us. After all, this is what hope is all about, isn’t it?

Memory flash cards from @makingwildpaper has been such a fun game lately for the Bear.

The Bear absolutely loves the book series "The Dinosaur that pooped", and thats where his love for dinosaurs began. He slowly started identifying some of the classic features of dinosaurs like the short hands of a t-rex and the long necked ones that eat leaves. 

I wanted to introduce dinosaurs to him without overwhelming him and these flash cards turned out to be an absolute delight. They portray dinosaurs in vibrant colors and distinguishing features with a little anecdote about each. 

I have lost count of the number of times we have already played them. It is still surprising to me how a simple set of cards like these can spark such joy and learning in these little minds.

node.text: Lovely to hear Simon’s story! Amazing account ?
Lovely to hear Simon’s story! Amazing account ?

Simon Hawkins, 30, is a nurse caring for urgent surgery patients at the Montefiore Hospital in Brighton, which was taken over by the NHS during the pandemic.
“People have been more nervous and understandably need a lot more TLC and looking after mentally,” he said.
In spite of the challenging conditions and working in full PPE, Simon said he felt lucky to be able to go to work during lockdown. There were other aspects he enjoyed too.
“It was great to be forced to slow down in my personal life. There were no interruptions and I was able to spend more time with my boyfriend Janusz. He’s a baker and has loved having time to make more elaborate things.”
Simon - pictured here with his dog Nigel - has lived in Brighton all his life. He says it’s difficult to visit Poland where his partner is from because of the political landscape, particularly since the recent re-election of President Andrzej Duda.
“He wants to eradicate the LGBT community and has set up LGBT-free zones. My boyfriend feels ashamed of it,” he said.
The couple, who met two years ago, have no plans to leave Brighton. 
“Nowhere else is as accepting. The people make it what it is. When I go on holiday I actually look forward to coming home. I always say it’s a lovely bubble here - a bubble I hope never bursts.”

But in general it gears up your mood,  the relaxation from heat, the new playlist for drive, the switch from chocolate shakes to hot chocolate, the guilt free fried food menu, after all we take only those things for granted which are the closest, case in point fried food here. All this most definitely gives you a different high.  I haven’t felt more connected to food what lockdown has made me feel. A deep sense of gratitude for every small ingredient that I get on time at my door step when I am genuinely craving to cook something fancy. Every plate I cook makes me so excited. Where was this feeling all these years? node.text:
Intended Pareidolia.
.
Pareidolia is the tendency of our mind to create patterns, and familiar shapes in otherwise random clusters of things. Like seeing shapes in clouds, familiar objects in stone and mud and of course, bodies and faces in trees.
.
I first saw this kind of art work on the backs of Mad Magazines where you'd have a random cluster of buildings or a complicated map or even a dark forest and then you fold the paper up or look at it upside down and it turns into another image. Usually something very funny! I miss Mad Magazines.
.
Anyone else a fan of MAD? And no I don't mean Pogo's music and dace segment hosted by the artist 'Rob'... Something. Who by the way incidentally, also did a lot of art work with intentional Pareidolia. (see how I segwayed back there? )
.
What do you see first when you see this post? Let me know in the comments.
.

node.text: Based in Beirut, Lebanese-Polish sisters Tessa and Tara Sakhi co-founded T SAKHI, a multidisciplinary architecture and design studio in 2016. In an increasingly fast paced world, the sister architects place human interaction at the core of their practice and question our contemporary understandings of identity and living. They design both permanent and ephemeral spaces & objects, drawing from the emotional and physical experiences by incorporating all five senses and memory.

node.text:
From modern residences, to portable nightclubs, re-adapted urban designs, or satiric dining installations, T Sakhi is an architecture and design studio where projects are are diverse, playful and interactive. They range from small-scale architecture, public and urban installations, commercial and residential design, collectible hand-made objects, scenography and film. Despite their versatile talents and contrasting affinities, the sisters and partners combine their duality to create a hybrid occidental-oriental inspiration and collaborate with creatives and artists from all over the world, provoking an exchange and dialogue to reach craftsmanship and innovation. 

Their work have been exhibited in Beirut, Paris, Milan and Dubai Design Weeks and donated in Philips’ London Auction house
